{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Finish Jira hard-delete -> outbound re-create (replaces lost epic-3e36)\n\n## Why\nOn a Jira hard-delete the reconciler preserves local content (ADR 0027/0028) BUT never re-creates the Jira\nissue — the `follow_on` re-create payload is built and never consumed, and the branch writes a COMMENT falsely\nclaiming \"outbound re-create follow-on emitted\". Finish the feature.\nCitations: `apply_inbound.py:541-560` (hard_delete branch, TODO(epic-3e36) at :560); `applier.py:469-471`\n(follow_on consumer only handles `kind==\"suppress_pair\"`); `reconcile.py:68-79`.\n\n## What (ONE consistent wiring — sentinel-dict follow-on, no contradiction)\n1. Key mismatch: `_apply_inbound_delete` branches on `payload.get(\"probe_outcome\")` but the prod probe router\n   emits `reason`. CANONICAL = `reason`: update `_apply_inbound_delete` to read `reason`; update the existing\n   unit-test fixture (the only current caller of the hard_delete branch) to match.\n2. Emit follow-on as a SENTINEL DICT `{\"kind\": \"create_after_hard_delete\", \"local_id\":..., ...}` (paralleling the\n   existing `{\"kind\":\"suppress_pair\"}`), NOT a typed Mutation from `_apply_inbound_delete`. (This supersedes the\n   earlier typed-Mutation phrasing — one shape only.)\n3. Consume it in `applier.py:469-471`: add a branch that, for `kind==\"create_after_hard_delete\"`, builds an\n   outbound create and routes it through `dispatch_one.create_one` (which has JQL dedup + `bind_confirm`) — NOT\n   `_apply_outbound_create` (that leaf lacks dedup + binding persistence). Injection point: in `apply()`, after\n   the inbound loop collects follow-ons, prepend the converted creates to the outbound list before `_apply_batch`.\n4. Idempotency: `create_one`'s JQL dedup + `recover_pending_bindings` prevent a double-create on retry; add a test.\n5. Stale-binding lifecycle: after re-create, `bind_confirm(local_id, new_key)` overwrites the forward mapping;\n   the dead old-key reverse entry is cleared on the same save (or, if it lingers, retired via the existing\n   `note_absent`->grace path — there is no public `retire(jira_key)` API, and none is added). Add a test asserting\n   the local_id ends bound to the NEW key and the dead key is not resurrected.\n6. Guard: only genuine `hard_delete` re-creates (redirect/out_of_window/trash do NOT); add a guard test.\n7. Fix the misleading COMMENT; log create/retire success+failure (observability). Partial-failure: if re-create\n   succeeds but rebinding fails, the next pass's dedup binds to the existing issue (no duplicate) — documented.\n8. Repoint `TODO(epic-3e36)` (apply_inbound.py:560) to THIS epic; clear the `.joe-janitor/report-2026-07-02.md:137` flag.\n\n## Scope\nEdit targets: `apply_inbound.py`, `applier.py`, `dispatch_one.py` (via existing `create_one`), tests. (`reconcile.py`\nonly if the dispatch table needs the sentinel — otherwise unchanged.)\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Canonical `reason` key; hard_delete branch reachable in the real dispatch path; unit-test fixture updated.\n- [ ] Follow-on is a `kind=\"create_after_hard_delete\"` sentinel dict consumed in `applier.py:469-471` and routed through `dispatch_one.create_one`; injected into the outbound batch in the same pass at the named point in `apply()`.\n- [ ] Idempotent: retry after partial failure does not double-create (test).\n- [ ] After re-create, local_id is bound to the NEW key; the dead old key is not resurrected (test); retirement uses existing APIs (no new `retire`).\n- [ ] Only genuine hard-deletes re-create (guard test); redirect/out_of_window/trash do not.\n- [ ] COMMENT accurate; create/retire logged; `TODO(epic-3e36)` repointed; janitor flag cleared.\n- [ ] End-to-end test: inbound hard-delete -> outbound re-create in one pass.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783476726567301001,"uuid":"15a4e149-1a50-49ba-ba99-a1fd0a30228b"}